        <div n="M40914W2" type="poem"><head type="note" n="1" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-headnote-1"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-headnote-1-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-headnote-1-line-group-1-line-1">IN THE NAME OF DR SWIFT.<ref target="#spp-M40914W2-footnote-1">1</ref><note n="1" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-footnote-1" place="foot">See Mrs Pilkington's Memoirs, Vol. III. page 65.──N</note></l></lg></head><head type="note" n="2" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-headnote-2"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-headnote-2-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-headnote-2-line-group-1-line-1"/></lg></head><head type="note" n="3" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-headnote-3"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-headnote-3-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-headnote-3-line-group-1-line-1"/></lg></head>
      <lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-line-1">M<hi rend="SMALL-CAPS">IGHTY</hi> Thomas, <ref target="#spp-M40914W2-footnote-1">1</ref><note place="foot" n="1" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-footnote-1">From their diminutive size, the Dean used to call Mr Pilkington “Tom Thumb,” and his wife “his lady fair.”──N.</note> a solemn senatus <ref target="#spp-M40914W2-footnote-2">2</ref><note place="foot" n="2" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-footnote-2">To correct Mrs Barber's poems; which were published at London, in 4to, by subscription.</note> I call,</l><l n="2" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-line-2"> To consult for Sapphira; <ref target="#spp-M40914W2-footnote-3">3</ref><note place="foot" n="3" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-footnote-3">The name by which Mrs Barber was distinguished by her friends.──N.</note> so come one and all;</l><l n="3" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-line-3"> Quit books, and quit business, your cure and your care,</l><l n="4" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-line-4"> For a long winding walk, and a short bill of fare.</l><l n="5" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-line-5"> I've mutton for you, sir; and as for the ladies,</l><l n="6" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-line-6"> As friend Virgil has it, I've <hi rend="underline">aliud mercedis</hi>;</l><l n="7" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-line-7"> For Letty, <ref target="#spp-M40914W2-footnote-4">4</ref><note place="foot" n="4" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-footnote-4">Mrs Pilkington.──N.</note> one filbert, whereon to regale;</l><l n="8" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-line-8"> And a peach for pale Constance, <ref target="#spp-M40914W2-footnote-5">5</ref><note place="foot" n="5" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-footnote-5">Mrs Constantia Grierson, a very learned young lady, who died in 1733, at the age of 27.──N.</note> to make a full meal;</l><l n="9" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-line-9"> And for your cruel part, <ref target="#spp-M40914W2-footnote-6">6</ref><note place="foot" n="6" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-footnote-6">Mrs Van Lewen, (Mrs Pilkington's mother,) who used to argue with Dr Swift, about his declamation against eating blood.──N.</note> who take pleasure in blood,</l><l n="10" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-line-10"> I have that of the grape, which is ten times as good:</l><l n="11" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-line-11"> Flow wit to her honour, flow wine to her health:</l><l n="12" xml:id="spp-M40914W2-line-12"> High raised be her worth above titles or wealth.M40914W2   </l></lg></div>
